rComments: I honestly loved Dr. Messier's courses, I made sure that I took his class for all upper year neuroanatomy courses. The weekly quizzes made it reasonable to learn and retain all of the content - something that I really appreciate now that I am in an experimental master's program.

Conflicted about this guy... I personally didn't find him all that engaging as a lecturer, but we had a 5 question quiz every class instead of midterms, all questions from textbook question bank. I thought the quizzes were fine, they were on iClicker REEF so you'd see tons of people opening Quizlet in another window to look up the question/cheat :/
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Beware of pop quizzes']

rComments: Quiz at the end of every class based on the textbook. The quizzes replace mid terms. Attendance is mandatory to do the quizzes (need to enable location on device to do quiz). The content in class is to enhance learning and is not tested. Overall engaging prof. Should be more respected by first years.

Messier is a good prof, very smart with many interesting stories. Instead of midterms he had quizzes worth 2% of our grade every class. At first it was great but it gets old quick, especially because they add up to 51% total. If you do the readings and pay attention they are an easy 5/5 but time to do that becomes at issue during the semester.

He had quizzes every class so attendance was mandatory - he tracked location so you can't do the quiz from home. His lectures are useless because everything is based off of the textbook anyways; he even said that what he says in class will never be tested on. Content is pretty easy and straightforward. He thinks he's funny - but he's really not
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: This was my first Psychology class and let me tell you, I will never be taking psychology again. Each class we had a quiz, which was worth 50% of your final mark and the other half was the exam. We were given virtually no instructions on what to study for the exam so you're basically left to memorize the entire textbook. I learnt nothing.
teacherRatingTags: ['Beware of pop quizzes', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: I learned a lot in his class. He is genuinely kind and very welcoming to students in office hours. He answers all questions and he encourages participation in class. I find the quizzes very useful and help students to interact with the course material. I would definitely take more classes with him.

Personally, I have no idea what I'm learning in this class, his lectures are all over the place and he tries to get students involved, but it ultimately doesn't work. He made attendance mandatory since we were given quizzes that went toward our grade every class. if I want to be an idiot and skip class, I should be able to on my own terms.

not a bad professor,but don't like him. he has quizzes for every class so you have to attend. do not try to skip the class but just do the quiz. he is professional but he can't answer the question clearly. going to the class can't let you learn knowledge cause he won't say anything helpful. recommend you to learn by yourself before the class.

Wouldn't recommend this class, Although his 2nd and 3rd year classes are easy, 4th year is definitely not an easy one. His quizzes and tests are extremely hard for this one and also his expectations are very unclear.

Amazing professor, especially when he tries to make neuro jokes to lighten the mood. Grading is based on daily quizzes (not hard if you read assigned material), one paper and one presentation. I would take him again, learned more this way than I have in other courses which use midterm/finals. He likes if you particiante and ask questions!!!

he is a nice man and is very knowledgeable about his field however it is an extremely challenging fourth-year course that will be as a heavy as 2 other courses. the grading scheme is not the best, I personally would not recommend this, especially to 4th year students with a full course load, a job or a thesis to do
teacherRatingTags: ['Beware of pop quizzes', 'Test heavy', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: hard hard hard hard hard hard. if you are doing a thesis (or have a hard class load) do NOT take this. you can thank me later... trust me!!
you are going to regret taking this. do NOT base it on his second and third-year classes, this is them on steroids.

nice ish guy, but the way the course is set up is bizarre, yes the third year one was easy but the fourth year is a NIGHTMARE. dont take it bc it seems interesting... trust me you'll be happy you didnt
teacherRatingTags: ['Test heavy', 'Beware of pop quizzes', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Really amazing! He is unorthodox (no midterms, no final) we had a 5 (easy) question s quiz every class, 2 page paper, and 1 5-minute presentation the whole semester. It sounds scarier than it is. He cares about his students. Not a harsh grader.

Really nice prof, he's very knowledgeable and smart. He does ramble on in class sometimes, but only because he is so passionate about the topic. Make sure you do the readings and work hard on your presentation and essay and you'll be good.

Every class there is a quiz on the pages he assigned to read. There's an oral presentation and a paper you have to write but no final.  Quizzes get annoying, and he doesn't lecture things related to the readings, but he's a good lecturer.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Lots of homework', 'Test heavy']

rComments: Read the textbook for pop quizzes before each class. Study the neuroanatomy because he randomly calls a handful of students up each class to do a quiz.  No final exam, just a paper and presentation.

LOVE him. Weekly material-based quizzes (2) plus a different, surprise quiz for whom the students are chosen randomly (neuroanatomy). It's a weekly commitment that's necessary to do well in his class but it's very easy to do well if you make that commitment. There was also a short paper and oral presentation. Follow his guidelines & you'll be fine.

I really enjoyed this class. I was kind of taken aback by how much work it was at first but he makes the class really fun and engaging. I definitely learned more in this class than 80% of my psych classes. Also, go to class and follow the syllabus. It's the easiest A you will ever get just by doing the work and showing up every class.

Phenomenal professor! There are in class quizzes every class but most of them are not too difficult if you do the reading. Every class he picks random students to do the Digital Anatomist (interactive brain atlas) - Google it. Seems scary but it's really easy! There's also a 5 min presentation and a paper which he marks fairly! Best part - NO EXAMS

Great method of pedagogy! No midterm, no final. One quiz every class in total worth 40%, neuroanatomy pop quizzes worth 30%, one oral presentation 5 min. worth 10% and one 2 page paper worth 20%. Very interesting material. Makes it bite-sized so it's easy to digest what could otherwise be a very difficult class. Highly recommend.

It's a little daunting at first, but there are two quizzes every class, one 5 question quiz based on a reading and a digital anatomist quiz where you point out brain regions. At first you'll want to run outta there but it's not too hard and it really keeps you on your toes. He conveys all the material really well and you can tell he knows his stuff

Excellent class... new favourite prof at uOttawa! Love the way he organized the course, with weekly mini quizzes, presentations and anatomy labeling. Although unconventional, the class was interactive and informative.  I like how when he had time he would sneak in mini-lectures about interesting and relevant research in neuroscience.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Lots of homework', 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: One of my favourite classes so far! His unconventional grading makes it really easy to get an A as long as you're willing to go to class and do the readings!

AWESOME prof! Knows a lot about neuroscience and the latest scientific developments. His grading scheme is unconventional but supported by science to ensure maximum success: mini quiz + anatomy labeling  + 5-min orals + his lecture   structure of every class. It forces you to read the assigned readings - so if you work hard to keep up   easy A!

Neuroscience class: One of my favourite classes and profs at Ottawa U. Super interesting class! Lots of projects so that you really learn instead of having to just memorize. Makes it so that you have to learn everything as you go instead of cramming so that you really understand.

His class is absolutely and terrifically engaging! NOT boring AT ALL. He is the think-outside-the-box type who is so eager to share his world of knowledge with the class. Even though the material is quite challenging (human neuropsych), he actually made it quite ea sy, and the textbook is great! His experiments are awesome too!
soooo boring, barely ever gone to class but really good textbooks lets me know eveyrthing i need to know and got A's on the exams.  Nice guy, but hard to keep interest for an hour and half
Very cute in a boyish grown up way!Course material sucks but he made it easier to get good marks. Love him as a prof.
Great prof, he made biological foundations a pleasure to learn. I loved his class!
He's is very very knowledgable about his field. Sometimes he moves a bit fast in class, but he always encourages questions and always answers them clearly. Is very friendly and makes the class fun.
Concentrates mainly on his notes for exams.  Very knowledgeable of biology.
